            <div class="opener__topic-title-dek-wrapper ">

                    <span class="opener__topics ">
            <a class="opener__topics-link " href="https://www.propublica.org/topics/regulation">Regulation</a>
        </span>
    
    <h1 class="opener__hed " >        Gone in 15 Days: How the Connecticut DMV Allows Tow Companies to Sell People’s Cars
    </h1>

    <h2 class="opener__dek " style="display: none" >        A law intended to deal with abandoned vehicles is making it hard for low-income people to get their cars back after they’re towed. The consequences can extend far beyond the cost of the car.
    </h2>
    </div> <!-- Close .opener__topic-title-dek-wrapper -->

</div>
        
<div class="article-meta-1
     article-meta-1--left     " data-pp-location="article meta">

    <span class="article-meta-1__byline" data-pp-location="article byine">
        by <a class="name" href="https://ctmirror.org/author/daltimari/">Dave Altimari</a> and <a class="name" href="https://ctmirror.org/author/gmonk/">Ginny Monk</a>, <a href="https://ctmirror.org/">The Connecticut Mirror</a>, and <a class="name" href="https://www.propublica.org/people/haru-coryne">Haru Coryne</a>, ProPublica    </span>
    <time class="article-meta-1__pubdate">
        <time class="timestamp" datetime="2025-01-05EST05:00">Jan. 5, 5 a.m. EST</time>
    </time>

    <div class="article-meta-1__section-actions
