<figcaption class="attribution">
    
    
    
    </figcaption>


</figure>

        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="34.0">That’s the system Anderson faced as she fought with MyHoopty and sought the DMV’s help.</p>

<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="34.1">“We live paycheck to paycheck and Christmas was coming, and we just couldn’t afford to try and get the car back,” Anderson said.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="35.0">Michael Festa, the owner of MyHoopty, said he is simply following the law, which allows property owners to remove cars that break rules. In an emailed response to written questions, Festa said he’s never turned over money to the state because the proceeds have never satisfied the towing and storage bill.</p>
        
    
                    
